trying to print the actual cycle, it attempts to access the NodeDefs involved

implementation is used: nodes can't be access when they are consumed.

[{"sha":"442c81ae3f8b370b9b9d20eaa7ec35dd7a78e011","author":{"name":"mergify[bot]","email":"b09a6ee808b67e98a221404e7aaa52e0398a4954@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"fix(ci) improve golden YAML matcher errors (#2759)

When the Gomega YAML matcher fails to match, it keeps some information
about the error in the match instance. When the golden output matcher
generates a new matcher instance on each ginkgo call, that internal
state is dumped and we get less error context.

The result of this fix is that the golden YAML matcher will now emit the
first mismatched key in the error, just like the underlying gomega YAML
matcher does.

Signed-off-by: James Peach <james.peach@konghq.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kumahq/kuma/commits/442c81ae3f8b370b9b9d20eaa7ec35dd7a78e011"}]

Add support for binding TrafficRoute resources to Gateways. This is
based on outbound proxy generator code, but there are still a number of
missing features and outstanding TODO items.

It is possible to configure simple HTTP Gateway use cases and forward
traffic to Kuma services as long as the mesh is not configures with mTLS.
A Gateway can have more than one TrafficRoute resource bound, and this
works correctly by merging the routes in match order.

Rewrote most of KDS mux as it wasn't working as intended.
KDS mux now ensures:

Send() on underlying streams are always called in the same goroutine
Close() actually waits for some goroutine to terminate
Also added extra tests to ensure these invariants

Fixes #2492

[{"sha":"0863618b348582096cb6b39e5069b1c44f946751","author":{"name":"Partha Aji","email":"f1580ee59435d07680e08f585e6382b2c892386d@redhat.com"},"message":"Fixes #33385,#33054,#33144 - Fixes host group inheritance (#9599)

Before the PR -

On create hostgroups page the inheritance hierachy behavior was different
between katello attribute like content_view/lce/content source etc vs
things like os and arch
For example if you create a child hostgroup and ppointed to a parent
with contnet view, you would see the cv automatically selected as the
default, instead of 'Inherit Content View' as os/arch fields behave.

More over if you had cv, lce, cs, arch filled in the parent hostgroup
and enabled operating system in the child the media section would not
get automatically populated (because the notion of parent_id was
 missing)

After:

Both the above cases behave appropriately.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Katello/katello/commits/0863618b348582096cb6b39e5069b1c44f946751"}]

[{"sha":"b27df0272962ad9fc7766d86db7542d6b7ab7f8d","author":{"name":"Katherine Wu","email":"3597b8ab71b66d46ec439caf0c075cd0b82fcc57@google.com"},"message":"Refactor SavedModel SaverDef implementation so that the save/restore functions are generated in the Eager context.

This change prepares the SavedModel code to allow users to register advanced checkpoint saving/restore functions.

The SaverDef is a SavedModel field that allows TF2 SavedModels to be compatible with TF1. Before this CL, the SaverDef is generated by copying all objects and resource tensors from the eager context/default graph to the SavedModel exported graph.

The object-copying will not work well when we start introducing custom objects and classes, so this change defines the save and restore functions in same context that the user is saving in.

The extra arguments in `GraphView.frozen_saveables` are removed, and there is a slight reshuffling of code to make things the functionality partitions clearer.

NEW:
The traced save/restore functions now create a dummy SaveableObject to be saved into the checkpoint when there are no saveables to save or restore.

The test in the original CL failed because the TPU converter did not filter out the  traced_save and traced_restore functions. The filter checks for the SaveV2/RestoreV2 ops, which the test-exported SavedModel did not have because the model had no variables.

[{"sha":"718fa3895f7364f75d0418595f15a31bb7b99ef7","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"backend: Remove Operation.Parallelism field

The presence of this field was confusing because in practice the local
backend doesn't use it for anything and the remote backend was using it
only to return an error if it's set to anything other than the default,
under the assumption that it would always match ContextOpts.Parallelism.

The "command" package is the one actually responsible for handling this
option, and it does so by placing it into the partial ContextOpts which it
passes into the backend when preparing for a local operation. To make that
clearer, here we remove Operation.Parallelism and change the few uses of
it to refer to ContextOpts.Parallelism instead, so that everyone is
reading and writing this value from the same place.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/718fa3895f7364f75d0418595f15a31bb7b99ef7"},{"sha":"332ea1f233891e45bd274e714ab8e4e11c79dc95","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"backend/local: TestLocal_plan_context_error to fail terraform.NewContext

The original intent of this test was to verify that we properly release
the state lock if terraform.NewContext fails. This was in response to a
bug in an earlier version of Terraform where that wasn't true.

In the recent refactoring that made terraform.NewContext no longer
responsible for provider constraint/checksum verification, this test began
testing a failed plan operation instead, which left the error return path
from terraform.NewContext untested.

An invalid parallelism value is the one remaining case where
terraform.NewContext can return an error, so as a localized fix for this
test I've switched it to just intentionally set an invalid parallelism
value. This is still not ideal because it's still testing an
implementation detail, but I've at least left a comment inline to try to
be clearer about what the goal is here so that we can respond in a more
appropriate way if future changes cause this test to fail again.

In the long run I'd like to move this last remaining check out to be the
responsibility of the CLI layer, with terraform.NewContext either just
assuming the value correct or panicking when it isn't, but the handling
of this CLI option is currently rather awkwardly spread across the
command and backend packages so we'll save that refactoring for a later
date.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/332ea1f233891e45bd274e714ab8e4e11c79dc95"}]

Leverage Envoy's :ffff prefix to be able to have AAAA and an A record

Signed-off-by: Jakub Dyszkiewicz <jakub.dyszkiewicz@gmail.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kumahq/kuma/commits/336d724a1ccfcc8706c64af81da42960300154b0"},{"sha":"dcb10a27ce0870a97b72a47011759c998fdf7789","author":{"name":"James Peach","email":"cfb385863e43a54966ce6ee8158f84aabd7009b9@konghq.com"},"message":"fix(ci) improve golden YAML matcher errors (#2759)

When the Gomega YAML matcher fails to match, it keeps some information
about the error in the match instance. When the golden output matcher
generates a new matcher instance on each ginkgo call, that internal
state is dumped and we get less error context.

The result of this fix is that the golden YAML matcher will now emit the
first mismatched key in the error, just like the underlying gomega YAML
matcher does.

Signed-off-by: James Peach <james.peach@konghq.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kumahq/kuma/commits/dcb10a27ce0870a97b72a47011759c998fdf7789"},{"sha":"13a2ffaddcaa68ab76b5de1a83de9c9a733a4d84","author":{"name":"James Peach","email":"cfb385863e43a54966ce6ee8158f84aabd7009b9@konghq.com"},"message":"fix(*) switch to a Kuma fork of go-control-plane (#2771)

control over the stability of releases, and can cherry-pick individual
fixes.

[{"sha":"2637c1540237c19733fcc90daf129fd8c1cbeeec","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Add a new config-proto option that enables CPU global JIT (aka autoclustering).

Before this change, CPU code would not be auto-jit'ed (i.e. autoclustered and
sent to XLA) unless the JIT level was >= ON_1 *and* the envvar TF_XLA_FLAGS
contained --tf_xla_cpu_global_jit.

The logic behind this is, if you have a GPU net, you probably *don't* want CPU
autojit.  CPU autojit can break up GPU clusters by sending metadata ops (which
are just ops on int32 tensors) to the CPU, instead of computing them cheaply on
the GPU.

This is right and fine, but a problem arises if you have a single binary that
mixes CPU and GPU nets and wants to autojit both of them.  You don't want to
autojit the CPU part of GPU nets, but you do want to autojit the CPU part of
CPU nets!  But the single envvar gets in your way.

None of this is perfect, but to make it slightly better, we introduce a new
flag, cpu_global_jit, that acts equivalently to the envvar, but is per-session
rather than global.

Now you can set the flag just on the CPU models that you're interested in
autojit'ing.

[{"sha":"8afeca44c1903af3bb00451f32553d963d32c175","author":{"name":"Fergus Henderson","email":"f0ea4d8809145d4adcbe42010b047377f121dc12@google.com"},"message":"NativeInterpreterWrapper refactoring: split applyDelegates.

This is a small refactoring that is a partial step towards the
goal of eventually replacing the use of the experimental C++
API method Interpreter::ModifyGraphWithDelegate with calls to
InterpreterOptions::AddDelegate.

This step splits the existing Java applyDelegates method into two,
addDelegates and applyDelegates, so we now add all the delegates
(except for the XNNPACK delegate) to the 'delegates' list before
constructing the interpreter; and also moves the place where the
delegates are applied closer to where the interpreter is constructed;
but we still use ModifyGraphWithDelegate to apply the delegates.

Change NativeInterpreterWrapper's useXNNPACK method so that instead of
directly applying the XNNPACK delegate using ModifyGraphWithDelegate,
it just constructs the delegate and returns it (and thus
also rename the method as CreateXNNPACKDelegate), and instead have the
caller add that delegate to the list of delegates that will get applied.

This required adding a Java type for XNNPack Delegate.
